<TITLE> <font size=1 color=black>WAR CRIMES TRIALS</font><br>Evidence sought from museum </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 30 (bdnews24.com)The war crimes investigative agency on Tuesday formally asked information from the Liberation War Museum about the perpetrators of crimes against humanity in 1971 . "We asked for evidence and documents on war criminals," head of the agency Abdul Matin told reporters after visiting the museum. He said the trustee board chief Mafidul Huq assured him of necessary cooperation. "We sought for evidence during Mar 25 to Dec 17, 1971," Matin said. Three members of the agencyAbdur Rahim, Mir Shaihdul Islam and Abdur Razzaqueand member of the lawyers panel Mosharraf Hossain Kajal were present during the visit. Regarding collection of data he said, "Information will be asked from different organisations and individuals. Evidences could be oral and technical". Notices will be issued against those accused. Kajal said, "The museum has over 14,000 documents and evidence, which will help a lot to probe crime. "We'll also collect some books, published from Pakistan, that have a lot of evidence on crimes committed during the war," he added. bd
